Real-Time Observability with 25 Grafana Dashboards in Production

In large cloud environments, troubleshooting without visibility is like searching in the dark. One of the most impactful improvements we implemented in our production environment was building 25 dedicated Grafana dashboards to monitor applications running across AWS, Azure, and GCP on VMs, EC2 instances, and Kubernetes clusters.

Instead of putting everything into one overloaded dashboard, we divided monitoring into multiple focused dashboards so that each team — DevOps, SRE, and Production Support — could quickly find the information they needed during incidents.

In our real production setup, Grafana is connected with Prometheus, cloud monitoring APIs, and log pipelines, allowing us to visualize infrastructure, application, and cluster metrics in real time.

For infrastructure monitoring, several dashboards focus on VM and EC2 health. These dashboards track CPU utilization, memory consumption, disk I/O, and network traffic. When there is a sudden spike in resource usage, the operations team can immediately identify which instance or service is impacted.

For Kubernetes environments, we created dashboards that monitor node health, pod status, container restarts, and namespace-level resource utilization. This helps us quickly identify issues like pods stuck in pending state, unexpected container crashes, or nodes running out of resources.

Another set of dashboards focuses on application performance monitoring. These dashboards display API request rates, response latency, error percentages, and service availability. When an application starts responding slowly or returning errors, these panels help engineers pinpoint the exact service causing the problem.

We also built database monitoring dashboards to track query load, connection counts, replication health, and storage growth. This allows the team to identify database bottlenecks before they affect user-facing applications.

To improve incident response, we integrated Grafana alerts with monitoring systems, so whenever thresholds are crossed, alerts are triggered and engineers can directly open the relevant dashboard to start investigation.

After implementing these 25 Grafana dashboards in production, the results were very clear:

• Faster incident detection
• Reduced troubleshooting time
• Better collaboration between DevOps and support teams
• Improved reliability across multi-cloud infrastructure

Grafana dashboards have become more than just visual charts for us — they act as a central visibility layer for our entire cloud ecosystem.

When systems grow across multiple clouds and container platforms, strong observability is what keeps everything running smoothly.
